  "prompt": "When will we lose muscle mass in our body?",
  "response": "Muscle mass can begin to decline for various reasons, and the timing can vary from person to person. Here are some common factors that contribute to muscle loss:\n\n1. **Aging**: Sarcopenia, the age-related loss of muscle mass, typically begins in the 30s and accelerates after age 60. The rate of muscle loss can be about 1-2% per year after the age of 50.\n\n2. **Inactivity**: Prolonged periods of inactivity, such as during bed rest or sedentary lifestyles, can lead to muscle atrophy. Even a few weeks without regular exercise can start to result in muscle loss.\n\n3. **Diet**: Insufficient protein intake or severe caloric restriction can contribute to muscle loss. It's important to maintain a balanced diet to support muscle health.\n\n4. **Illness and Injury**: Conditions such as chronic illness, injury, or surgery can also promote muscle loss due to reduced activity levels, hormonal changes, or increased metabolic demands.\n\n5. **Hormonal Changes**: Changes in hormones, such as decreased testosterone and estrogen levels, can affect muscle mass, especially in older adults.\n\n6. **Stress and Sleep**: Chronic stress and lack of sleep can lead to hormonal changes that may negatively affect muscle mass.\n\nTo mitigate muscle loss, maintain a regular exercise routine that includes strength training, consume adequate protein, and lead an active lifestyle. If you have concerns about muscle mass or related health issues, consulting with a healthcare or fitness professional can provide personalized advice.",
